full_text.12: In the license to IBM, Gates negotiated the “non-exclusive rights” meaning he could resell that operating system to as many hardware manufacturers as he wanted to.
full_text.13: Gates knew of an operating system that he could purchase for $75k that he thought could fit the specs IBM needed. He bought the system and renamed it MS-DOS.
full_text.14: Gates decided to license IBM an operating system for $250k, the only problem was Gates didn’t have one built yet but he had an idea.
full_text.15: They asked Gates to provide the operating system for their new hardware and he declined—referring IBM to his friend Gary Kildall. Luckily for Gates, Kildall didn’t want to sign an NDA and wanted royalties instead of a lump sum for the project. IBM came back to Gates for help.
